HTTP = HyperText Transfer Protocol (a language used by client and server to communicate)
  Stateless - each request is independent
    Request-Response - client asks, server answers
      Standard format - everyone uses same rules

HTTP Methods (Verbs)
==================================================================================================================GET
GET - "Give me data"
  Client: "GET /api/tasks"
    Meaning: "Show me all tasks"
      Server responds: List of all tasks

Real example:
javascript
  fetch('http://localhost:5000/api/tasks', {
    method: 'GET'  // ← GET method
})
==================================================================================================================POST
POST - "Create new data"
  Client: "POST /api/tasks"
    Body: {name: "Study Python", description: "Learn OOP"}
      Meaning: "Create a new task with this data"

Server responds: The newly created task

Real example:
  javascript
    fetch('http://localhost:5000/api/tasks', {
      method: 'POST',  // ← POST method
       body: JSON.stringify({
        name: "Study Python",
          description: "Learn OOP"
    })
})
==================================================================================================================PUT
PUT - "Replace entire data"
  Client: "PUT /api/tasks/1"
    Body: {name: "NEW NAME", description: "NEW DESC"}
      Meaning: "Replace task #1 with this new data"
        Server responds: Updated task
==================================================================================================================PATCH
PATCH - "Update partial data"
  Client: "PATCH /api/tasks/1"
    Body: {is_complete: true}
      Meaning: "Update only the is_complete field of task #1"
        Server responds: Updated task
==================================================================================================================DELETE
DELETE - "Remove data"
  Client: "DELETE /api/tasks/1"
    Meaning: "Delete task #1"
      Server responds: "Task deleted"
==================================================================================================================STATUS CODES
HTTP Status Codes
200 Series - Success 
  200 OK - Request successful, here's the data
    201 Created - Request successful, new resource created
      204 No Content - Request successful, no data to return
        400 Series - Client Error 
          400 Bad Request - You sent bad data
            401 Unauthorized - You need to login
              403 Forbidden - You don't have permission
                404 Not Found - Resource doesn't exist
                  500 Series - Server Error 
                    500 Internal Server Error - Server messed up
                      503 Service Unavailable - Server is down

Real example:

javascript
  fetch('http://localhost:5000/api/tasks')
    .then(response => {
        if (response.status === 200) {
            console.log("Success!");
        } else if (response.status === 404) {
            console.log("Task not found!");
        } else if (response.status === 500) {
            console.log("Server error!");
        }
    })
==================================================================================================================HTTP REQUEST STRUCTURE
HTTP Request Structure
  Every HTTP request has this structure:

REQUEST LINE:  GET /api/tasks HTTP/1.1
  HEADERS:       Host: localhost:5000
               Content-Type: application/json
               Authorization: Bearer token123
BLANK LINE:
BODY:          {"name": "Study Python"}
Breaking It Down
---------------------------------------------------
Request Line:
GET /api/tasks HTTP/1.1
├─ GET = HTTP method
├─ /api/tasks = endpoint (path)
└─ HTTP/1.1 = protocol version

Headers:
Host: localhost:5000              ← Where server is
Content-Type: application/json    ← Data format
Authorization: Bearer token123    ← Authentication token

Body:
{"name": "Study Python", "description": "Learn basics"}
==================================================================================================================HTTP RESPONSE STRUCTURE
HTTP Response Structure
Server sends back:

STATUS LINE:   HTTP/1.1 201 Created
HEADERS:       Content-Type: application/json
               Content-Length: 125
BLANK LINE:
BODY:          {"id": 1, "name": "Study Python", "is_complete": false}
Breaking It Down

Status Line:

HTTP/1.1 201 Created
├─ HTTP/1.1 = protocol
├─ 201 = status code
└─ Created = status message

Headers:

Content-Type: application/json    ← Data format of body
Content-Length: 125               ← Size of body

Body:

{"id": 1, "name": "Study Python", "is_complete": false}
==================================================================================================================URLs & END POINTS
URLs & Endpoints
https://localhost:5000/api/tasks/1
├─ https:// = protocol (secure)
├─ localhost = domain/server address
├─ :5000 = port number
├─ /api/tasks/1 = endpoint (path)
└─ /1 = specific resource ID
Endpoint Patterns
GET    /api/tasks              ← Get all tasks
POST   /api/tasks              ← Create new task
PUT    /api/tasks/1            ← Update task #1
PATCH  /api/tasks/1/complete   ← Mark task #1 complete
DELETE /api/tasks/1            ← Delete task #1

Same /api/tasks with different methods = different actions
Adding /1 makes it specific to that task
Adding /complete makes it a specific action
