==================================================================================================================COMMUNICATION OF BACKEND AND FRONTEND
How Frontend and Backend Communicate

Frontend (Your Browser)
    ↓
    HTTP Request (asks backend for something)
    ↓
Backend (Flask Server)
    ↓
    HTTP Response (sends answer back)
    ↓
Frontend (receives and displays)

A client is anything that requests something.
Examples:
- Your web browser
- Your phone app
- Your computer
- Anyone using your app

What is a Server?
A server is anything that provides something.
Examples:
- Flask app running on localhost:5000
- Google's servers
- Facebook's servers
- Any app serving data

How they Communicate
Client: "Hey server, give me all tasks"
    ↓ (HTTP Request)
Server receives request
Server: "Here are your tasks"
    ↓ (HTTP Response)
Client receives response and displays it
==================================================================================================================EXAMPLE
Step 1: User Types Credentials

Browser shows login form
User enters: username="carl", password="secret"
User clicks: Login button
----------------------------------------------------
Step 2: Frontend Makes HTTP Request
javascript
fetch('http://localhost:5000/api/login', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json'
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
        username: "carl",
        password: "secret"
    })
})
----------------------------------------------------
Step 3: HTTP Request Sent
POST /api/login HTTP/1.1
Host: localhost:5000
Content-Type: application/json
Content-Length: 45

{"username":"carl","password":"secret"}
----------------------------------------------------
Step 4: Backend Receives & Processes
python
@app.route('/api/login', methods=['POST'])
def login():
    data = request.get_json()  # Gets the JSON body
    username = data.get('username')  # "carl"
    password = data.get('password')  # "secret"
    
    # Check if valid
    if username == "carl" and password == "secret":
        token = "abc123xyz"
        return jsonify({"token": token}), 200
    else:
        return jsonify({"error": "Wrong credentials"}), 401
----------------------------------------------------
Step 5: HTTP Response Sent Back
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: application/json
Content-Length: 25

{"token":"abc123xyz"}
----------------------------------------------------
Step 6: Frontend Receives Response
javascript
.then(response => response.json())
.then(data => {
    console.log(data.token)  // "abc123xyz"
    localStorage.setItem('token', data.token)
    window.location.href = 'index.html'
})
